#compdef blades
# =============================================================================
# blades — Maroš Grego's "Blazing fast dead simple static site
#           generator" — a Rust-based SSG that emphasizes raw
#           build speed + minimal dependencies over feature
#           breadth.  Distinguishing from Hugo/Zola/11ty by:
#             - Minimal config (TOML) + content (Markdown +
#               frontmatter) + Ramhorns templates (a fast
#               Rust Mustache-derivative)
#             - PLUGIN PROTOCOL: external commands can supply
#               input pages, transform pages, generate output
#               assets — all via JSON-line stdin/stdout
#               communication
#             - LAZY BUILD MODE (default): only re-colocate
#               assets if the theme changed (saves time on
#               iterative builds)
#             - TAXONOMIES: tag/category-like content
#               organization with configurable hierarchies
#             - Sub-second builds on most sites (the README
#               claims thousands-of-pages sites build in
#               under a second)
#             - SINGLE-FILE OUTPUT: no client-side JavaScript
#               required — pure HTML output by default
#           Used by minimalist bloggers, technical
#           documentation sites, and developers who want a
#           Rust-toolchain SSG without the complexity of
#           Hugo's template language or Zola's heavier
#           feature surface.
#
# Author:  Maroš Grego (grego on GitHub) — Slovak Rust
#          developer; launched blades in 2021 as the fast
#          minimal SSG he wanted for his own sites.  Continues
#          active maintenance with periodic releases.
# Source:  https://github.com/grego/blades
#          https://github.com/grego/blades/blob/master/src/main.rs
# CLI:     src/main.rs — uses hand-rolled argv parsing (matches
#          `env::args().nth(1)` against known subcommand
#          strings).  Headline error library: `thiserror`
#          (David Tolnay) for derive-based structured error
#          enums in the build pipeline + config loader +
#          plugin protocol layer.
# Library: thiserror (David Tolnay / dtolnay)
#          ("derive(Error)" — David Tolnay (dtolnay GitHub) —
#           released 2019 as the COMPANION LIBRARY TO ANYHOW
#           (also by Tolnay) for STRUCTURED ERROR ENUMS in
#           Rust libraries.  Where anyhow (R598) provides a
#           single type-erased error type for APPLICATIONS,
#           thiserror provides DERIVE MACROS for defining
#           structured error enums in LIBRARIES — the
#           library/application split codified.
#           thiserror's central feature: the `#[derive(Error)]`
#           proc-macro that auto-generates `impl std::error::
#           Error` for user-defined error enums with
#           per-variant `#[error("...")]` format-string
#           attributes, `#[from]` for automatic From-conversion
#           between error types, `#[source]` for chained
#           source-error attribution, and `#[backtrace]` for
#           backtrace integration.)
# License: GPL-3.0 (blades); MIT OR Apache-2.0 (thiserror)
# Status:  blades — 347+ stars on grego/blades, active
#          maintenance with monthly releases; thiserror —
#          3600+ stars on dtolnay/thiserror (top-40 Rust
#          GitHub project), 700M+ all-time crates.io downloads
#          (paired with anyhow as the canonical
#          library+application error-handling stack), found-
#          ational dependency of tens of thousands of Rust
#          libraries throughout the ecosystem.
#
