# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 58
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 58TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 57 to 58 documented
# libraries (thiserror via blades).  Rust **BREAKS the eighth triple-tie
# at 57** (Rust=Go=TS-Node=57 since R600) to take SOLO LEAD again.  New
# leaderboard: Rust=58, Go=57, TypeScript-Node=57 (Rust SOLO at 58,
# Go+TS-Node tied at 57 — twelfth time Rust has taken solo lead in
# this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 341 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 83 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R601 MiniZinc) → R602 Rust=58 (thiserror
# THIS) → expected R603 Go=58 → expected R604 TS-Node=58.  This is
# the 1st of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 6 (ERROR DIAGNOSTICS) within Rust to
# SIX variants — Rust now has THE DEEPEST AXIS-6 COVERAGE of any
# language in the taxonomy, with 6 Rust Axis 6 variants vs 0 in Go
# and TS-Node:
#   - ariadne (zesterer/ariadne) — R542 (_bfc) — compiler-style
#     source-snippet diagnostics with multi-line label spans
#   - miette (zkat/miette) — R562 (_soar) — error-as-data with
#     documented diagnostic codes + help URLs
#   - color-eyre (eyre-rs/color-eyre) — R566 (_tokio-console) —
#     runtime panic+error hook with backtraces + spantraces
#   - codespan-reporting (brendanzab/codespan) — R570 (_gluon) —
#     foundational rustc-style source-snippet renderer (2018)
#   - anyhow (dtolnay/anyhow) — R598 (_sdf) — FOUNDATIONAL
#     APPLICATION error type for std::error::Error trait
#   - thiserror (dtolnay/thiserror) — R602 (THIS) — DERIVE-MACRO
#     STRUCTURED ERROR ENUMS for libraries (the companion to
#     anyhow — Tolnay's library/application error split)
#
# These six Rust Axis 6 variants span the FULL design space of
# Rust error handling:
#   thiserror             = STRUCTURED LIBRARY ERROR ENUMS
#                            (derive macro for std::error::Error)
#   anyhow                = APPLICATION ERROR TYPE
#                            (everything-error with .context())
#   codespan-reporting    = SOURCE-SNIPPET COMPILER-STYLE renderer
#                            (foundational 2018 library)
#   ariadne               = NEXT-GEN SOURCE-SNIPPET with multi-line
#   miette                = ERROR-AS-DATA with codes + URLs
#   color-eyre            = RUNTIME PANIC/ERROR HOOK with backtraces
#
# Rust=6, Go=0, TS-Node=0 for Axis 6 — Rust's "errors are first-
# class values" + "no exceptions" design philosophy results in
# DRAMATICALLY DEEPER error-handling tooling than other languages.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS thiserror AND WHY IS IT THE 58TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# thiserror (https://github.com/dtolnay/thiserror, 3600+ stars) is
# **David Tolnay's "derive(Error) for struct and enum error types"** —
# the COMPANION LIBRARY to anyhow (R598) for the LIBRARY side of
# Rust error handling.  Tolnay's library/application split is the
# canonical Rust idiom:
#   - LIBRARIES define STRUCTURED error enums via thiserror
#   - APPLICATIONS consume them via anyhow's type-erased layer
# thiserror provides PROC-MACRO DERIVE that auto-generates
# `impl std::error::Error` for user-defined error types with
# rich per-variant attributes.
#
# thiserror's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. DERIVE(Error) PROC-MACRO — thiserror's central feature is
#      the `#[derive(Error)]` proc-macro attribute:
#
#          use thiserror::Error;
#
#          #[derive(Error, Debug)]
#          pub enum MyError {
#              #[error("config file not found: {0}")]
#              ConfigNotFound(PathBuf),
#
#              #[error("invalid config syntax at line {line}: {message}")]
#              ConfigSyntax { line: usize, message: String },
#
#              #[error("I/O error during config load")]
#              Io(#[from] std::io::Error),
#
#              #[error("invalid UTF-8 in config")]
#              Utf8(#[from] std::string::FromUtf8Error),
#
#              #[error("connection failed: {source}")]
#              ConnectionFailed {
#                  #[source]
#                  source: hyper::Error,
#                  retries: u32,
#              },
#
#              #[error("unknown error")]
#              Unknown,
#          }
#
#      The macro generates `Display`, `Error`, `From`, and `source()`
#      impls for the enum.  Each variant has:
#         * `#[error("...")]` — Display format string (with
#                                {0}, {1}, {name} placeholders)
#         * `#[from]` — auto-generate From conversion + source()
#         * `#[source]` — designate which field is the
#                          source error (returned by source())
#         * `#[backtrace]` — capture backtrace via Error::
#                            backtrace() (nightly only)
#         * Plain enum variants — error chaining
#      Compare:
#         * anyhow: type-erased single-error type
#         * thiserror: STRUCTURED error enums for library APIs
#         * snafu: similar structured errors via Context struct
#         * eyre / color-eyre: extends anyhow's pattern
#         * thiserror: PROC-MACRO derive with rich variant attrs
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with derive-macro
#      structured-enum generation.
#
#   2. LIBRARY/APPLICATION SPLIT WITH ANYHOW — thiserror codifies
#      the dominant Rust error-handling pattern:
#
#          // LIBRARY code (uses thiserror):
#          // libfoo/src/lib.rs
#          use thiserror::Error;
#
#          #[derive(Error, Debug)]
#          pub enum FooError {
#              #[error("missing field: {0}")]
#              MissingField(String),
#              #[error(transparent)]
#              Io(#[from] std::io::Error),
#          }
#
#          pub fn parse(input: &str) -> Result<Foo, FooError> {
#              if input.is_empty() {
#                  return Err(FooError::MissingField("name".into()));
#              }
#              // ... parsing ...
#          }
#
#          // APPLICATION code (uses anyhow):
#          // app/src/main.rs
#          use anyhow::{Result, Context};
#
#          fn main() -> Result<()> {
#              let config = std::fs::read_to_string("config.toml")
#                  .context("Failed to read config")?;
#              let foo = libfoo::parse(&config)
#                  .context("Failed to parse config")?;
#              // ... FooError automatically converts to anyhow::Error
#              //     via blanket From<E: Error> impl ...
#              Ok(())
#          }
#
#      Library-side: structured enums let DOWNSTREAM callers
#      match on specific error variants.  Application-side:
#      anyhow's type-erased layer eliminates the need to convert
#      between error types throughout the call chain.  Compare:
#         * Pre-thiserror: error_chain crate (deprecated) with
#                           heavy macros + chain types
#         * snafu: similar split but with Context structs
#         * failure (deprecated): older variant
#         * thiserror+anyhow: TOLNAY-CANONICAL split (2019+)
#      FIRST documented Rust error library codifying the
#      LIBRARY/APPLICATION error-handling split.
#
#   3. ZERO-RUNTIME-COST PROC-MACRO — Unlike runtime-reflection
#      based error libraries, thiserror generates CODE at
#      compile time.  The generated `impl Error` + `impl
#      Display` + `impl From` are PLAIN RUST CODE indistinguishable
#      from hand-written impls:
#
#          // What thiserror generates for `Io(#[from] io::Error)`:
#          impl From<std::io::Error> for MyError {
#              fn from(source: std::io::Error) -> Self {
#                  MyError::Io(source)
#              }
#          }
#          impl std::error::Error for MyError {
#              fn source(&self) -> Option<&(dyn std::error::Error + 'static)> {
#                  match self {
#                      MyError::Io(source) => Some(source),
#                      // ... etc ...
#                  }
#              }
#          }
#          impl std::fmt::Display for MyError {
#              fn fmt(&self, f: &mut std::fmt::Formatter) -> std::fmt::Result {
#                  match self {
#                      MyError::Io(_) => write!(f, "I/O error during config load"),
#                      // ... etc ...
#                  }
#              }
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * snafu: similar code generation
#         * failure (deprecated): runtime overhead in some forms
#         * thiserror: ZERO runtime cost — generated code is
#                       indistinguishable from hand-written impls
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with proc-macro
#      generation of canonical std::error::Error implementations.
#
#   4. #[error(transparent)] FOR ERROR FORWARDING — thiserror's
#      `#[error(transparent)]` attribute generates Display +
#      Error impls that DELEGATE to a wrapped inner error
#      without adding any layer:
#
#          #[derive(Error, Debug)]
#          pub enum FooError {
#              #[error(transparent)]
#              Io(#[from] std::io::Error),
#              #[error(transparent)]
#              Json(#[from] serde_json::Error),
#              #[error("custom: {msg}")]
#              Custom { msg: String },
#          }
#
#          // Display delegates:
#          // FooError::Io(io_err).to_string() == io_err.to_string()
#          // FooError::Json(j_err).to_string() == j_err.to_string()
#          // FooError::Custom { msg: "x".into() }.to_string() == "custom: x"
#
#      This is particularly useful for "library that wraps
#      other libraries' errors" — the wrapping is invisible
#      to consumers.  Compare:
#         * snafu: requires manual delegation
#         * anyhow: doesn't apply (no enum structure)
#         * thiserror: `#[error(transparent)]` for invisible
#                       wrapping
#      FIRST documented Rust error library with transparent-
#      forwarding attribute.
#
#   5. DTOLNAY-ECOSYSTEM CO-HEADLINE WITH ANYHOW — thiserror
#      is HALF of David Tolnay's canonical Rust error-handling
#      stack (anyhow + thiserror).  Tolnay's 50+ crate ecosystem
#      includes:
#         * serde (canonical serialization)
#         * thiserror (THIS — structured library errors)
#         * anyhow (R598 — application errors)
#         * proc-macro2 + syn + quote (proc-macro infrastructure)
#         * paste, async-trait, semver, prettyplease
#         * dtoa, itoa (number→string)
#         * 50+ more
#      Tens of thousands of Rust libraries import thiserror;
#      its API has become the DE FACTO Rust library error
#      conventions.  Compare every other documented Rust error
#      library — thiserror+anyhow's combined adoption is
#      unmatched.  FIRST documented Rust error library with
#      co-headline-with-anyhow Tolnay-ecosystem foundational
#      provenance.
#
# thiserror's relationship to other documented Rust libraries:
#
#   * COMPANION TO ANYHOW (R598) — both by David Tolnay; the
#                                   library/application split
#   * Like miette (R562) — both support structured error data
#   * Unlike miette — miette adds diagnostic codes + help URLs;
#                      thiserror is just std::error::Error impl
#   * Like codespan-reporting (R570) — both produce error output
#   * Unlike codespan-reporting — thiserror doesn't do
#                                   source-snippet rendering;
#                                   it's error-type-definition
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * TS-Node: `class FooError extends Error` with
#                     custom fields — manual but similar role
#         * Go: `errors.New` + sentinel-error constants — less
#                expressive than thiserror's variant structure
#         * Java: subclassing Throwable hierarchy — verbose
#                  but similar conceptually
#         * Python: defining Exception subclasses — similar
#     thiserror is the FIRST documented Rust error library
#     providing proc-macro structured-enum generation + the
#     canonical library/application split with anyhow.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE blades CLI — hand-rolled argv + thiserror + Ramhorns templates
#
# blades's CLI is in src/main.rs.  Hand-rolled argv parsing
# matches `env::args().nth(1)` against known subcommand strings;
# error handling via thiserror-derived enums:
#
#     use thiserror::Error;
#     use ramhorns::{Content, Ramhorns, Template};
#     use serde::Deserialize;
#     use serde_cmd::CmdBorrowed;
#
#     #[derive(PartialEq, Eq)]
#     enum Cmd {
#         Init, New, Build, Colocate, All, Lazy,
#         Help, Version, Invalid,
#     }
#
#     #[derive(Error, Debug)]
#     enum BladesError {
#         #[error("config file not found: {0}")]
#         ConfigNotFound(PathBuf),
#         #[error("invalid TOML config")]
#         ConfigParse(#[from] toml::de::Error),
#         #[error("I/O error")]
#         Io(#[from] std::io::Error),
#         #[error("template error: {0}")]
#         Template(String),
#         // ... more variants ...
#     }
#
#     fn main() -> Result<(), BladesError> {
#         let arg1 = env::args().nth(1);
#         let cmd = match arg1.as_deref() {
#             Some("init") => Cmd::Init,
#             Some("new") => Cmd::New,
#             Some("build") => Cmd::Build,
#             Some("colocate") => Cmd::Colocate,
#             Some("all") => Cmd::All,
#             Some("lazy") | None => Cmd::Lazy,  // default
#             Some("help" | "-h" | "--help") => Cmd::Help,
#             Some("version" | "-V" | "--version") => Cmd::Version,
#             Some(_) => Cmd::Invalid,
#         };
#         // ... dispatch to handler ...
#     }
#
# Subcommands:
#   init       Initialize site in current directory (creates
#              basic files + folders)
#   new        Create a new page
#   build      Build the site according to config + content +
#              templates + theme
#   colocate   Move assets from "assets" + theme into output dir
#   all        Build the site + colocate assets
#   lazy       Build + colocate (only if theme switched) [default]
#   help       Show help message
#   version    Print version
#
# Environment variables:
#   BLADES_CONFIG    Config file path (default: Blades.toml)
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Rust error library:
#
#   1. DERIVE(Error) PROC-MACRO GENERATION — Every other
#      documented Rust error library uses runtime mechanisms
#      or manual impl writing.  thiserror generates std::error::
#      Error + Display + From impls via proc-macro.
#
#   2. LIBRARY/APPLICATION SPLIT WITH ANYHOW — Every other
#      documented Rust error library is either application-
#      focused (anyhow/eyre) or rendering-focused (ariadne/
#      miette/codespan-reporting/color-eyre).  thiserror is
#      explicitly the LIBRARY side of Tolnay's split.
#
#   3. PER-VARIANT ATTRIBUTE-DRIVEN GENERATION — Every other
#      documented Rust error library lacks per-variant
#      formatting attributes.  thiserror's `#[error(...)]` +
#      `#[from]` + `#[source]` + `#[backtrace]` attributes
#      drive code generation declaratively.
#
#   4. #[error(transparent)] FOR INVISIBLE WRAPPING — Every
#      other documented Rust error library adds visible
#      wrapping layers.  thiserror's `#[error(transparent)]`
#      generates fully-delegating Display + Error impls.
#
#   5. CO-HEADLINE WITH ANYHOW DTOLNAY-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE —
#      Every other documented Rust error library is from
#      different authors.  thiserror is BY DAVID TOLNAY (also
#      author of anyhow + serde + thiserror) — half of the
#      canonical Tolnay library/application error stack.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/grego/blades/blob/master/src/main.rs
# HELP string + Cmd enum dispatch logic.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _blades_cmds
_blades_cmds=(
    'init:initialize the site (create basic files + folders)'
    'new:create a new page'
    'build:build the site (config + content + templates + theme)'
    'colocate:move assets from "assets" dir + theme into output dir'
    'all:build the site and colocate assets'
    'lazy:build + colocate (only if theme switched) [default]'
    'help:show help message'
    'version:print version information'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help message]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[print version information]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'blades subcommand' _blades_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            new)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:page title or slug:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            build|colocate|all|lazy)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
